Okay.

124
00:12:03,188 --> 00:12:08,174
So, uh, this is, this is reflections on death.

125
00:12:08,195 --> 00:12:09,616
Let me just turn this down a bit.

126
00:12:12,039 --> 00:12:12,561
Okay.

127
00:12:14,160 --> 00:12:16,563
So I'll read this just as it comes.

128
00:12:16,625 --> 00:12:18,527
It's not very long, so hang on in there.

129
00:12:20,230 --> 00:12:31,085
Remember, the Buddhist scriptures were all handed down in the verbal tradition of remembering the discourses one after the other.

130
00:12:31,105 --> 00:12:33,948
So they can tend to be a bit repetitious.

131
00:12:33,969 --> 00:12:40,118
But when you read them with the purpose of absorbing, the repetition actually does come through.

132
00:12:43,067 --> 00:12:50,076
Thus have I heard, at one time the Buddha was staying at Savati in Jeta's Grove and at the Pindika's Park.

133
00:12:50,096 --> 00:12:51,638
So that was one of his main monasteries.

134
00:12:52,859 --> 00:13:00,807
At that time, the Blessed One said to the monastics, you should cultivate the perception of death and give attention to the perception of death.

135
00:13:01,568 --> 00:13:09,597
Although the word is perception here, I think we probably would get closer to the idea of contemplating death.

136
00:13:10,067 --> 00:13:13,933
or how you perceive death maybe, how you relate to death.

137
00:13:15,155 --> 00:13:24,168
Then one monastic among those seated there said to the Blessed One, I constantly cultivate giving attention to the perception of death.

138
00:13:25,070 --> 00:13:31,879
And the Blessed One said, how do you give attention to the cultivating of the perception of death?

139
00:13:32,140 --> 00:13:37,729
The monastic said to the Buddha, at the time of giving attention to the perception of death,

140
00:13:38,148 --> 00:13:46,302
I have the aspiration to remain alive for seven days and give attention to the seven awakening factors.

141
00:13:46,322 --> 00:13:54,979
In the Tathagata's teachings, that's the Buddha Tathagata, that's what he called himself, the transcendent one, that's what it means.

142
00:13:55,500 --> 00:14:02,011
In the Tathagata's teaching, that would be of much benefit and I will not regret passing away after that.

143
00:14:02,802 --> 00:14:06,427
Blessed one, it is like this that I give attention to the perception of death.

144
00:14:06,788 --> 00:14:12,837
So his aspiration is to stay alive for seven days and to contemplate the seven factors of awakening.

145
00:14:13,698 --> 00:14:16,724
And the blessed one says, stop, stop, monastic.

146
00:14:18,225 --> 00:14:21,971
This is not truly an undertaking of the practice of the perception of death.

147
00:14:22,293 --> 00:14:25,498
This is called being of a negligent nature.

148
00:14:25,878 --> 00:14:26,919
That's not very nice, is it?

149
00:14:28,705 --> 00:14:33,990
Now, again, one monastic said to the Blessed One, I am capable of cultivating the perception of death.

150
00:14:34,431 --> 00:14:38,615
And the Blessed One said, how do you cultivate attending to the perception of death?

151
00:14:38,715 --> 00:14:42,418
And the monastic said to the Buddha, now I have this reflection.

152
00:14:43,139 --> 00:14:46,464
I have the aspiration to remain alive for six days.

153
00:14:46,844 --> 00:14:55,572
And having given attention to the right teachings of the Tathagata, that might reach the end, then might reach the end of my life.

154
00:14:56,296 --> 00:14:58,480
This will thus be my good fortune.

155
00:14:58,720 --> 00:15:01,183
And in this way, I attend to the perception of death.

156
00:15:01,464 --> 00:15:12,402
So he's hoping to die after six days, during which he will attend or will contemplate the teachings of the Buddha.

157
00:15:12,582 --> 00:15:16,769
And the Blessed One said, stop, stop, monastic.

158
00:15:16,789 --> 00:15:18,993
You are also of a negligent nature.

159
00:15:19,594 --> 00:15:21,898
This is not attending to the perception of death.

160
00:15:23,110 --> 00:15:27,618
Now, again, the monastic said to the Buddha, I aspire to remain for five days.

161
00:15:28,600 --> 00:15:31,024
I aspire to remain alive for five days.

162
00:15:31,586 --> 00:15:35,833
And someone said, and then somebody else says, I aspire to remain alive for three days.

163
00:15:36,855 --> 00:15:39,039
I aspire to remain alive for two days.

164
00:15:39,279 --> 00:15:44,409
And one of them said, finally, I aspire to remain alive for one day.

165
00:15:45,823 --> 00:15:50,589
Now, at that time, the Blessed One said to the monastics, stop, stop, monastic.

166
00:15:50,609 --> 00:15:52,951
This is also being of a negligent nature.

167
00:15:53,471 --> 00:15:56,635
This is not truly attending to the perception of death.

168
00:15:57,756 --> 00:16:06,046
Now, at that time, there was again one monastic who said to the Blessed One, I am able to cultivate the perception of death effectively.

169
00:16:06,746 --> 00:16:15,797
And the monastic said to the Buddha, when the time has come, I put on my robes, take the alms bowl and enter sovereignty to beg for alms.

170
00:16:16,384 --> 00:16:22,494
Having begged for alms, I turn back to leave Sarvati and return to my place.

171
00:16:23,596 --> 00:16:28,583
I enter my meditation hut and give attention to the seven factors of awakening.

172
00:16:29,625 --> 00:16:31,587
Then I might reach the end of life.

173
00:16:31,948 --> 00:16:34,493
It is thus that I attend to the perception of death.

174
00:16:34,913 --> 00:16:39,139
So he's got no idea about one day, two days and so forth.

175
00:16:39,240 --> 00:16:45,109
He's just going to contemplate the seven factors of enlightenment and then he's happy to go.

176
00:16:45,712 --> 00:16:49,378
And the Buddha says to him, stop, stop, monastics.

177
00:16:49,398 --> 00:16:54,346
This is also not giving attention to the cultivation of the perception of death.

178
00:16:55,126 --> 00:16:59,373
Monastics, you all spoke of negligent ways of practicing.

179
00:17:00,094 --> 00:17:03,458
This is not the nature of cultivating the perception of death.

180
00:17:05,280 --> 00:17:08,346
Now, at that time, the Blessed One spoke to the monastics.

181
00:17:09,067 --> 00:17:12,632
Those who are able to be like the monastic vikarli,

182
00:17:13,269 --> 00:17:17,940
that they are indeed reckoned to have the attention to the perception of death.

183
00:17:18,922 --> 00:17:26,857
That monastic is well able to give attention to the perception of death, being disenchanted with this foul and unclean body.

184
00:17:27,444 --> 00:17:33,511
Now, the Buddha doesn't look upon the body as something that we should indulge.

185
00:17:34,633 --> 00:17:36,515
It's not something that we should delight in.

186
00:17:36,535 --> 00:17:40,660
We shouldn't be concerned about how beautiful it is, etc., etc.

187
00:17:41,480 --> 00:17:47,728
And to sort of get to that level is to recognize that beneath the skin, there aren't very many pleasant things.

188
00:17:48,449 --> 00:17:53,654
So he's always directing us to really be very practical about the body.

189
00:17:55,761 --> 00:18:14,144
So if a monastic gives attention to the perception of death, collecting his mindfulness in front, which means being mindful here and now, with a mind that is unshaken, being mindful of the exhalation and the inhalation for the time it takes for them to go out and return.

190
00:18:14,483 --> 00:18:23,895
And during that period, he gives attention to the seven factors of awakening that would indeed be of much benefit in the Tathagata's teachings.

191
00:18:24,936 --> 00:18:25,076
Right.

192
00:18:25,630 --> 00:18:27,392
So it's like one breath.

193
00:18:27,471 --> 00:18:31,296
I don't quite know how you can attend to the seven factors.

194
00:18:31,376 --> 00:18:37,163
I suppose you're just being aware that you are aware, aware of the breath, you see.

195
00:18:37,202 --> 00:18:39,705
So in other words, you're being within the moment.

196
00:18:39,766 --> 00:18:41,468
I think that's what this is saying.

197
00:18:42,469 --> 00:18:45,633
This is because all formations are entirely empty.

198
00:18:46,253 --> 00:18:47,855
They all become appeased.

199
00:18:47,915 --> 00:18:49,196
They rise and cease.

200
00:18:49,576 --> 00:18:53,561
They are all a magical illusion that is without any true essence.

201
00:18:53,862 --> 00:18:56,244
So again, it's this business of not self.

202
00:18:56,384 --> 00:19:01,972
It's seeing that, in fact, there is the breath, but the self, but there's nobody actually breathing.

203
00:19:02,173 --> 00:19:03,154
It's just the organism.

204
00:19:03,295 --> 00:19:06,618
It's the organism that is breathing in and breathing out.

205
00:19:07,180 --> 00:19:17,413
And you can get that sense when, you know, you've discovered within yourself that observation post where you're distancing from it and you see it as an object.

206
00:19:18,295 --> 00:19:22,401
So remember, the perceiver can't be the perceived.

207
00:19:23,106 --> 00:19:25,790
The one who sees an object can't be the object.

208
00:19:25,851 --> 00:19:31,460
The object is an object, not the subject.

209
00:19:31,480 --> 00:19:47,204
Therefore, monastics, you should give attention to the perception of death in the interval between the out-breath and the in-breath, so that you will be liberated from birth, old age, disease, death, grief, worry, pain and vexation.

210
00:19:47,365 --> 00:19:49,788
And in this way, monastics, you should train yourself.

211
00:19:50,208 --> 00:20:00,066
Now, as I understand this and as I've practiced it myself, as you breathe in and then breathe out, there's a break, isn't there, you see?

212
00:20:00,405 --> 00:20:03,692
So that's the end of that process, the end of that breath.

213
00:20:04,433 --> 00:20:10,765
And it's bringing that sense of ending more and more into our lives that actually brings you into the present moment.

214
00:20:11,452 --> 00:20:19,000
I'm sure those of you who've been here know that I go on about after a meal that this is one less meal in my life.

215
00:20:19,480 --> 00:20:20,721
This is one less breakfast.

216
00:20:20,740 --> 00:20:22,803
This is one less porridge in my life.

217
00:20:22,883 --> 00:20:26,487
I mean, it's a horror story, really, a continual horror story.

218
00:20:26,547 --> 00:20:34,753
But it's bringing into our awareness that we are actually moment to moment ending.

219
00:20:35,634 --> 00:20:37,135
We're very aware of the beginning of things.

220
00:20:37,175 --> 00:20:38,116
That's not a problem.

221
00:20:38,136 --> 00:20:40,278
We're always there at the start of something.

222
00:20:40,681 --> 00:20:42,202
but it's actually catching the end.

223
00:20:44,585 --> 00:20:51,031
Now, at that time, the monastics, hearing what the Buddha had said, were delighted and received it respectively.

224
00:20:55,135 --> 00:20:55,576
Very good.

225
00:20:55,836 --> 00:21:02,403
So that's the, I hope that gives you some indication on how to practice perception of death.

226
00:21:03,163 --> 00:21:07,328
The thing is to do it regularly for very small periods of time.

227
00:21:07,949 --> 00:21:09,590
You know, after every

228
00:21:09,892 --> 00:21:16,141
after every sitting or the beginning of a sitting, you know, just to bring to mind that we're living on a tightrope.

229
00:21:16,161 --> 00:21:19,184
We're living on a knife edge and you can fall off anytime, you know.

230
00:21:19,625 --> 00:21:27,817
So breathing in, breathing out, and then recognizing at this moment, you know, death could come to me or there could be death.

231
00:21:28,097 --> 00:21:30,540
Yeah.

232
00:21:30,561 --> 00:21:32,064
So time moves on.

233
00:21:33,005 --> 00:21:38,633
If there's any questions, do send me questions.

234
00:21:39,592 --> 00:21:41,440
By email, please, by email.

235
00:21:43,448 --> 00:21:48,690
And I think that just about does it.

